  "response": "**Finding to fix:** `crime_00004` — Half-UTC, Half-Local in `src/date.ts`.\n\n**Receiver identifier:** `d` — it's read with `getUTCFullYear()` at line 9 (UTC family) and `getMonth()` at line 41 (local family). The two families silently disagree by the host's UTC offset, so any year/month combination derived from `d` can land on the wrong calendar day near midnight.\n\n**Function to fix first:** the one containing line 41 (the local-family `getMonth()` call on `d`, which is also tied to the Date-string concatenation in `crime_00026` and is therefore the formatter). The line-9 site is already on the UTC family, so the formatter is the outlier.\n\n**Proposed refactor — pick the UTC family throughout:**\n\n```ts\n// before (mixed: getUTCFullYear + getMonth on the same d)\nreturn d.getUTCFullYear() + \"-\" + (d.getMonth() + 1) + \"-\" + d.getUTCDate();\n\n// after (all UTC, zero-padded, no hand-rolled concat)\nreturn d.toISOString().slice(0, 10);   // \"YYYY-MM-DD\" in UTC\n```\n\nRationale for choosing UTC over local:\n- The line-9 callsite already commits to UTC; converting *it* to local would change stored/serialized values and ripple through anything that reads them.\n- `crimes` recommends \"UTC for storage and local only at the display boundary\" — this file looks like storage/formatting, not a render-time formatter.\n- `toISOString()` also resolves the sibling findings on this line: `crime_00026` (string-sewing) and the zero-padding bug implicit in `+ (d.getMonth() + 1) + \"-\"`.\n\nIf a display string is needed in the user's locale, do that at the call site with `Intl.DateTimeFormat('en-US', { timeZone: 'UTC', … }).format(d)` — keep `d`'s reads UTC-only inside `date.ts`.",
